  "texts": [
    "The actual effectiveness of singing against big cats in India (man-eating tigers) was first noted by Corbett (1944), story of Chowgarh tigers.",
    "Corbett does not specify if the singing was in dissonances, we only know that it was a group singing.",
    "Generally, the effectiveness of singing as a \"tool for intimidation\" increases from singing alone, to singing with more persons; and also, from singing without harmony, to singing with harmony, and even more to singing with dissonant harmony.",
    "Basically, all kinds of singing are effective, but group singing in dissonant harmonies is the most effective.",
    "African Pygmies also use singing when going through the jungle, or, when they believe there is a danger of the attack from leopards at night (Turnbull, 1961, p. 58; Knight and Lewis, 2017)."
  ],
